  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initial efforts to combat financial crimes emerged in the early 20th century\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive legislative framework targeting financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established recordkeeping and reporting requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- Recommended international cooperation in tracking illicit financial flows\n- Established money laundering as a specific criminal offense\n\n4. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - 1989:\n- Intergovernmental organization developing global anti-money laundering standards\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national legal frameworks\n- Established international cooperation mechanisms\n\n5. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- US Patriot Act (2001)\n- Expanded financial reporting requirements\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Increased penalties for financial crimes\n\n6. Modern Regulatory Landscape:\n- Comprehensive global regulatory framework\n- Increased focus on digital currencies and emerging financial technologies\n- Continuous adaptation to evolving financial crime techniques\n\nThis overview highlights the progressive development of money laundering legal prohibitions.",
